<activity xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="act-2-1-1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use the three rules above to determine the derivative of each of the following functions.
      For each, state your answer using full and proper notation,
      labeling the derivative with its name.
      For example, if you are given a function <m>h(z)</m>,
      you should write <q><m>h'(z) =</m></q>
      or <q><m>\frac{dh}{dz} =</m></q> as part of your response.
      <ol label="a." cols="3">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f(t) = \pi</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>g(z) = 7^z</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>h(w) = w^{3/4}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>p(x) = 3^{1/2}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>r(t) = (\sqrt{2})^t</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>s(q) = q^{-1}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>m(t) = \frac{1}{t^3}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      <ol label="a.">
        <li>
          <p>
            Is <m>\pi</m> a variable or a constant?
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Is <m>g</m> a power or exponential function?
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Is <m>h</m> a power or exponential function?
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Is <m>3^{1/2}</m> a constant or a variable?
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is a constant
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Remember the notation here means
            <q>take the derivative with respect to <m>q</m> of <m>q^{-1}</m>.</q>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Rewrite the fraction using a negative exponent.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </hint>
  <answer>
    <p>
      <ol label="a.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f'(t) = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>g'(z) = 7^z \ln(7)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>h'(w) = \frac{3}{4} w^{-1/4}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{dp}{dx} = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>r'(t) = (\sqrt{2})^t \ln (\sqrt{2})</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{d}{dq}[q^{-1}] = -q^{-2}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{dm}{dt} = -3t^{-4} = -\frac{3}{t^4}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </answer>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol label="a.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f(t) = \pi</m> is constant, so <m>f'(t) = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>g(z) = 7^z</m> is an exponential function,
            so <m>g'(z) = 7^z \ln(7)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>h(w) = w^{3/4}</m> is a power function,
            thus <m>h'(w) = \frac{3}{4} w^{-1/4}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>p(x) = 3^{1/2}</m> is constant,
            and therefore <m>\frac{dp}{dx} = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>r(t) = (\sqrt{2})^t</m> is exponential
            (since <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is a constant),
            and so we have <m>r'(t) = (\sqrt{2})^t \ln (\sqrt{2})</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{d}{dq}[q^{-1}] = -q^{-2}</m>,
            by the rule for power functions.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>m(t) = \frac{1}{t^3} = t^{-3}</m>,
            so <m>\frac{dm}{dt} = -3t^{-4} = -\frac{3}{t^4}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</activity>

